Credit EDA Case Study¶

Vijaykumar Rangvani, Shruti Gupta¶

01-12-2021¶

In this case study, we will be performing risk analysis for the banking and financial services domain.Using exploratory data analysis, we are aiming to identify various factors and patterns that can be helpful in minizing the risk of loosing money while lending to customers.

In [43]:
#Dealing with outliers using 1.5 IQR method for selected column
for check in check_outliers: 
    q1 = app_df[check].quantile(0.25)
    q3 = app_df[check].quantile(0.75)
    iqr = q3-q1
    range_low  = q1-1.5*iqr
    range_high = q3+1.5*iqr
    app_df = app_df.loc[(app_df[check] > range_low) & (app_df[check] < range_high)]

# Dividing DAYS_BIRTH column into groups and storing it in new AGE_GROUPS column
def DAYS_BIRTH_CAT(DAYS_BIRTH):
    if DAYS_BIRTH <= 30:
        return 'Young'
    elif DAYS_BIRTH > 30 and DAYS_BIRTH <= 50:
        return 'Mid Age'
    else:
        return 'Old'
    
app_df['AGE_GROUPS'] = app_df['DAYS_BIRTH'].apply(DAYS_BIRTH_CAT)

#Creating the function proportion inorder to visualize the proportions of defaulters.
def proportion(val,r):
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,5))
    prop = pd.DataFrame(app_df.groupby([val])['TARGET'].value_counts()/app_df.groupby([val])['TARGET'].count())*100
    prop.columns = ['Per_Target']
    target = pd.pivot_table(prop, values ='Per_Target', index = val,columns =['TARGET'], aggfunc = np.sum) 
    target = target.reset_index()
    target.drop(0, axis = 1, inplace = True)
    target.columns = [val,'Non-default']
    ax2 = sns.barplot(x= val, y= 'Non-default',palette="muted", data= target)
    ax2.set_xlabel(f'{val}', fontsize=16,fontweight= 10,color='Blue')
    ax2.set_ylabel('Proportion of default',fontsize=16,fontweight= 10,color='Blue')
    ax2.set_title(f'Proportion of default w.r.t {val}', fontsize=24,fontweight= 7,color='Black')
    ax2.set_xticklabels(ax2.get_xticklabels(), rotation = r, fontsize = 18, color="Black")
    plt.show()

#Creating the function segmented_table inorder to segment-wise visualize different columns 
def segmented_table(df,val1,val2,r):
    plt.rcParams['figure.figsize']=(15, 6)
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,6))
    sns.set_style("white")
    col = pd.DataFrame(df.groupby([val1,val2])['TARGET'].value_counts()/df.groupby([val1,val2])['TARGET'].count())*100
    col.columns = ['Per_Target']
    target = pd.pivot_table(col, values ='Per_Target', index = [val1,val2],columns =['TARGET'], aggfunc = np.sum) 
    target = target.reset_index()
    target.drop(0, axis = 1, inplace = True)
    val1_val2 = pd.pivot_table(target,values=1, index =[val2],columns =[val1], aggfunc = np.sum) 
    plot = val1_val2.plot(kind='bar')
    plot.set_xlabel(f'{val2}', fontsize=16,fontweight= 10,color='Blue')
    plot.set_ylabel('Default(%)',fontsize=16,fontweight= 10,color='Blue')
    plot.set_title(f'Rate of Default by different {val1} and {val2}\n', fontsize=24,fontweight= 7,color='Black')
    plot.set_xticklabels(plot.get_xticklabels(), rotation = r, fontsize = 18, color="Black")
    plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1.02, 1), loc='upper left', borderaxespad=0)
    plt.show()

A. Calcution of top 10 Correlation¶

In [94]:
#Function for finding top 10 correlation 
#code from - https://stackoverflow.com/questions/17778394/list-highest-correlation-pairs-from-a-large-correlation-matrix-in-pandas

def top_correlation (df,n):
    corr_matrix = df.corr()
    correlation = (corr_matrix.where(np.triu(np.ones(corr_matrix.shape), k=1).astype(np.bool))
                 .stack()
                 .sort_values(ascending=False))
    correlation = pd.DataFrame(correlation).reset_index()
    correlation.columns=["Variable_1","Variable_2","Correlation"]
    correlation = correlation.reindex(correlation.Correlation.abs().sort_values(ascending=False).index).reset_index().drop(["index"],axis=1)
    return correlation.head(n)

In [111]:
#Dealing with outliers using 1.5 IQR method for selected column
for check in check_outliers: 
    q1 = prev_df[check].quantile(0.25)
    q3 = prev_df[check].quantile(0.75)
    iqr = q3-q1
    range_low  = q1-1.5*iqr
    range_high = q3+1.5*iqr
    prev_df = prev_df.loc[(prev_df[check] > range_low) & (prev_df[check] < range_high)]

  • Contact center is most popular channel for previous application data.

Conculsion¶

Safe Clients - These are the category or group that bank can target or approve loan for them as these groups are having minimal Default risk.

Old Age Group Clients.
State servant Clients.
High income category Clients.
Female clients in old age Group.
Client having higher education.
Clients with previous loan status as approved.
Widow Category clients can be targeted.

Risky Clients - These are the category or group that bank can avoid to approve loans as these clients have higher chances of Default associated with them.

  • Client having Lower secondary education.
  • Male clients with civil marriage.
  • Clients with previous loan status as cancelled or refused.
